, England":"Lenton, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Salceto","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Luis, Francisco, Rafael, Ana, Jesus, Carlos, Manuel, Miguel, Pedro, Jorge.","Spanish: habitational name from any of numerous places called Salcedo, named with a collective form of <i>salce</i> ‘willow tree’, or a topographic name denoting someone living by willow trees. Compare   Saucedo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Salcido","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Jesus, Carlos, Juan, Ruben, Luis, Roberto, Raul, Francisco, Juana, Adelina.","Hispanic (Mexico): probably an altered form of Spanish   Salcedo  ."]},{"name":"Saucedo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Jesus, Manuel, Carlos, Luis, Francisco, Raul, Miguel, Roberto, Alfredo, Guadalupe.","Spanish: variant of   Salcedo  . Compare   Sausedo  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":83,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":92,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Salceto II was born in 1132, in Lenton, Nottinghamshire, England as the son of Robert de Salceto I and Aveline de Montefaltrel. He had at least 2 sons. He died in 1236, at the age of 104."},"et":{"1132–1236":"1132–1236","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1162–1264":"1162–1264","1108–1175":"1108–1175","–Female":"Surnud","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","before 1132":"enne 1132","1132":"1132","1264":"1264","1175":"1175","1162":"1162",